Another important tip is to use your legs. Many players rely too much on their arms to generate power, but your legs are actually your biggest source of power. Make sure to bend your knees and use your leg strength to drive the ball forward. This will give you more power and control over your shots.

Finally, practice your follow-through. A good follow-through is essential for maintaining balance and control after hitting the ball. Make sure to finish your swing with a smooth, fluid motion, and keep your eye on the ball until it leaves your racket. This will help you hit more consistent and accurate shots.

Tip number four, and this is a big one. You want to make sure you're hitting the ball with your dominant hand. Now, I'm right-handed, so my right hand is my dominant hand. And when I'm hitting the ball, I want to make sure that my right hand is in control of the shot. That means my right shoulder is going to be lower than my left shoulder, and my right elbow is going to be bent. Now, if you're left-handed, it's going to be the opposite. Your left shoulder will be lower, and your left elbow will be bent. But the principle is the same. You want to make sure your dominant hand is in control of the shot. And how do you do that? Well, you're going to drop your hitting shoulder down, and you're going to bend your elbow. And that's going to give you the power and the control you need for your forehand. So remember, dominant hand in control, elbow bent, and shoulder dropped. That's tip number four.

The liver shot and spleen shot are indeed two of the most devastating body punches in boxing. The liver shot, when executed correctly with the left hand for a right-handed fighter or the right hand for a southpaw, can cause immense pain and potentially knock out an opponent. The spleen shot, on the other hand, can lead to serious internal injuries and is known to incapacitate fighters quickly.

When practicing these shots, it's crucial to focus on proper technique. The punch should be thrown with a rotational movement, transferring weight from the back foot to the front foot, and the hips should twist to generate maximum power. It's also important to keep the head and upper body moving to avoid counterattacks.

In the video, we see the individual demonstrating the proper stance and movement required for delivering an effective liver shot and spleen shot. The emphasis on stepping offline and dipping the weight down is key to generating the necessary force and precision. These are advanced techniques that require practice and conditioning, but mastering them can significantly enhance a boxer's arsenal.

Tip number four, and this is a big one. Many times players will hit the ball in the net because they're not getting enough racket head speed. And racket head speed comes from the rotation of the hips and the shoulders. So when you're hitting your forehand, remember to rotate those hips and shoulders. The more you can rotate, the more racket head speed you'll get, and that will help you clear the net. Now, I know what you're thinking, "Tom, how do I rotate my hips and shoulders?" Well, it's simple. When you're in your ready position, your feet should be shoulder-width apart. And when you go to hit the ball, your front foot should step into the shot, and your back foot should pivot on the balls of your feet. That will allow you to rotate your hips and shoulders, and get that racket head speed. And remember, the more you rotate, the more power you'll get on your forehand. So don't be afraid to really turn those hips and shoulders, and let that racket fly. Okay, so there you have it, four tips for improving your forehand technique. Alright, so we've got our athlete here in a seated position. He's gonna be doing some seated runs. Notice how he's keeping his elbows tight to his body, creating that 90-degree angle with his arms. This is crucial for maintaining proper form and maximizing the effectiveness of the exercise.

Now, as he starts to move, you'll see him bring his hips up and extend his legs. This is where the neuromuscular training comes into play. He's working on hip flexion and squeezing those quads. The goal is to engage those quick twitch muscles, which are responsible for explosive movements.

Remember, the key here is to keep everything in line. No bowing of the elbows outwards. We want to keep them nice and tight, right by the body. And let's not forget about the legs. They should be straight and in line with the torso. This will help ensure that the athlete is targeting the right muscles and getting the most out of the exercise.

So, there you have it. Neuromuscular training with seated runs. It's all about form, control, and engaging those quick twitch muscles. Thanks for tuning in, and remember to always train with sacrifice.

Place your stomach on the ball, with your arms extended in front of you and your legs straight back. Lift your right arm and left leg off the ground, hold for a second, then lower back down. The spleen shot, on the other hand, can lead to serious internal injury and is known for its long-term effects on the recipient.

A boxer needs to be in a proper stance, with their feet shoulder-width apart and their weight evenly distributed, to deliver maximum force.

The video shows a rugby match where the players are wearing orange and maroon jerseys. The scene is set on a grassy field with a clear sky above. The players are engaged in a tackle and breakdown situation, which is a critical aspect of rugby gameplay.

The player in the orange jersey is tackled by the player in the maroon jersey, and as he falls to the ground, he must release the ball immediately. The tackler must then get up and move away from the ball, allowing the attacking team to retrieve it. The breakdown midpoint is established where the players are in contact, not necessarily where the ball is.

The attacking team, now that they have possession of the ball, must ensure that only players acting as halfbacks can play the ball with their hands. These players must be on their feet and onside, meaning they must be behind the hindmost foot of the last player in the tackle. The offside line at the breakdown is determined by the back foot of the last player in the tackle.

The desired outcome of this breakdown is for the attacking team to maintain possession of the ball and continue their attack, while the defending team must retreat and not interfere with the play. The players must adhere to the laws of the game, ensuring fair play and safety for

The video continues with the instructor demonstrating the correct posture for riding, emphasizing the importance of seat bone positioning and its effect on the rider's torso. She explains that when the seat bones point down, the rider achieves a neutral spine, which is essential for maintaining balance and control while riding. The instructor uses her hands to illustrate the concept, pointing downwards to indicate the direction the seat bones should be facing.

She then shows how rounding the back changes the position of the seat bones, causing them to point in a different direction. This change in posture can lead to incorrect riding techniques, such as lifting the thighs off the saddle and losing the proper lower leg position. The instructor stresses that this can result in the rider losing their balance and not being able to effectively communicate with the horse.

The instructor introduces the concept of "line three," where the rider has completely lost the correct posture, and "line one," where the muscles are correctly engaged around the back. She explains that the thighs need to rotate in and "snug in" to create an A-frame around the horse, providing the ideal hold. She concludes by mentioning that at the end of each module, participants will be asked to send photographs or videos for feedback on their progress in mastering these techniques.

Alright, so we're gonna start with the back fist. Remember, it's all about power and momentum. You want to sink that punch in and follow through completely. Don't just hit and return, train your body to carry all the way through. Now, as you pull back, your front hand is going to roll over and grab. This isn't just a grab, it's a trapping motion. You're taking control of your opponent's arm, removing their power hand out of the way, and creating an opening for your next strike.

Notice how Sifu Cuddle steps back as he grabs. This is what he calls a "stealing step." It's a quick, efficient way to create distance and avoid a counterattack. And then, boom! He advances in with a nice rotating punch right to the stomach. That's where you want to aim - solar plexus or even lower to the groin if you can get it there.

This combination may look simple, but there's a lot of strategy behind it. By grabbing and trapping with your front hand, you're not only defending yourself, but you're also setting up your opponent for the next strike. And remember, always follow through with your punches. That's where the real power comes from.

Tip number four, and this is a big one. Many times players will hit the ball in the net because they're not getting enough racket head speed. And racket head speed comes from the shoulder. So you want to make sure that your shoulder is turning. Now, if you notice, my shoulder here is closed off. My chest is closed off. I'm not facing the net. And as I swing up, my shoulder opens up. My chest opens up. That's where the power comes from. That's where the racket head speed comes from. So remember, keep your shoulder closed off, and let it open up as you swing up. And that's going to give you the racket head speed you need to clear the net and get some pace on your shot. So there you have it, four quick tips for the forehand. Remember, swing low to high, get the racket at least a foot below the contact point, keep the racket face closed, hit the equator of the ball, and let your shoulder turn for racket head speed. Practice these tips, and you'll be hitting forehands like a pro in no time.

Alright, now that we've covered the basics of tipping the ski and understanding the role of the foot and ankle in initiating the movement, let's talk about how to apply this to a parallel turn. One of the most important things to remember is that you want to stay balanced over your skis throughout the turn. This means that your weight should be evenly distributed between both skis, with a slight emphasis on the inside ski during the turn.

As you start to initiate the turn by tipping the ski, you'll notice that your body will naturally want to lean into the turn. This is good! It means you're starting to engage the right muscles and movements. However, it's important not to let your body get too far ahead of your skis. You want to keep your upper body relatively quiet and stable, while your lower body does the work of turning the skis.

Another key thing to remember is to keep your knees bent and flexible. This will help you absorb any bumps or irregularities in the snow and maintain control throughout the turn. And don't forget to keep your eyes looking where you want to go – this will help you stay focused and make smoother, more controlled turns.

So, to recap: tip the ski with your foot and ankle, stay balanced

The liver shot and spleen shot are indeed powerful techniques in boxing, targeting the opponent's vital organs. The liver shot, delivered with the left hand for a right-handed boxer or the right hand for a southpaw, aims to strike the liver just below the floating ribs on the opponent's right side. This punch can be devastating, often causing the opponent to double over in pain and potentially leading to a knockout.

The spleen shot, on the other hand, targets the spleen located on the left side of the body. This punch can cause significant internal damage and is known to result in painful after-effects such as bruising or even bleeding.

When executing these shots, it's crucial to maintain proper footwork and balance. Stepping offline slightly and dipping the body helps generate power and accuracy. The punch should be thrown with an upward motion, almost like shoveling, which adds to the impact of the blow.

It's important to note that while these punches can be highly effective, they also require precision and control to avoid causing serious injury. Boxers must be trained and experienced to use these techniques safely and effectively in the ring.

The liver shot and spleen shot are indeed powerful techniques in boxing, targeting the opponent's vital organs. The liver shot, delivered with the left hand for a right-handed boxer or the right hand for a southpaw, aims to strike the liver just below the floating ribs on the opponent's right side. This punch can be devastating, often causing the opponent to double over in pain and potentially leading to a knockout.

The spleen shot, on the other hand, targets the spleen located on the left side of the body. This punch can cause significant internal damage and is known to result in painful after-effects for the recipient, such as bruising or even bleeding.

When executing these shots, it's crucial to maintain proper form and technique. The boxer should step offline slightly, dip their weight down onto the lead leg, and then push off the foot while punching upwards into the target area. The motion is akin to shoveling, where the boxer digs in and throws the punch over their shoulder.

For the spleen shot, the process is similar but involves stepping outwards for better balance. It's important to keep the other hand up for defense and to quickly retract the punching hand back to the guard position after the strike.

The video shows a rugby match where the players are practicing the new tackle and breakdown laws. The players in orange jerseys are on offense, while the players in maroon jerseys are on defense. The ball carrier in orange is tackled by a player in maroon, and the tackle assist releases immediately. The ball carrier passes the ball to a teammate who is on his feet and onside. The teammate then runs with the ball, and the defense retreats. The breakdown commences when a player from the attacking team is on their feet and over the ball, which is on the ground. Only players acting as a halfback can play the ball with their hands, and they must be on their feet and onside. The offside line at the breakdown is the back foot, and all arriving players must come from an onside position and can enter their side of the breakdown midpoint. Players must remain on their feet, and no players at the breakdown can have their hands on the ground beyond the ball or hold on, lean on, or have knees on players on the ground. Players off their feet sealing the ball will be penalized. Arriving players are encouraged to drive over and pass the ball.

The liver shot and spleen shot are indeed powerful techniques in boxing, targeting the opponent's internal organs. The liver shot, delivered with the left hand for a right-handed boxer or vice versa, aims to strike the liver just below the floating ribs on the opponent's right side. This punch can be devastating, often causing the opponent to double over in pain and potentially leading to a knockout.

The spleen shot, on the other hand, targets the spleen located on the left side of the body. This punch can cause significant internal damage and is known to result in painful after-effects for the recipient, such as bruising or even bleeding.

When executing these shots, it's crucial to maintain proper form and balance. The boxer should step offline slightly, dip their weight down onto the lead leg, and then push off that leg while punching upwards into the target area. The motion is akin to shoveling, where the boxer digs in and throws the punch over their shoulder.

It's important to note that these punches require precision and timing. The boxer must keep their other hand up for defense and ensure they follow through with the punch, bringing their hand back to a guard position after striking. Practicing these techniques repeatedly will help improve execution and effectiveness in the ring.

Alright, so let's talk about the grip. The grip is very important for your forehand technique. You want to make sure you're using a semi-western grip or an eastern grip. The semi-western grip is probably the most popular grip used by professional players today. It allows for a lot of topspin and control. The eastern grip is a little more flat, but it's still a great option if you're looking for a bit more reach and power.

Now, let's focus on the stance. Your feet should be shoulder-width apart, with your knees slightly bent. This will give you a stable base and allow you to transfer your weight properly through the shot. Remember, your weight should shift from your back foot to your front foot as you swing through the ball.

Another important aspect is the follow-through. After you've made contact with the ball, your racket should continue to move forward and up, finishing high and across your body. This will help you generate more power and spin on your shots.

And finally, practice, practice, practice! The more you practice your forehand technique, the better you'll become. Try hitting balls with different spins and speeds to get a feel for how the racket responds. And don't forget to work on your foot

The video shows a rugby match where the players are demonstrating the new tackle and breakdown laws that were trialed in NZ domestic competitions in 2016. The commentary explains that the tackler must get up before playing the ball and can only play it from behind his side of the breakdown midpoint, which is the point where players are in contact, not the ball itself. The player who has been tackled must immediately pass or release the ball and move away from it. If there is only one tackler, there is no breakdown or offside line, and open play continues with subsequent attacking players being able to be tackled by retreating defenders. The commentary emphasizes the importance of players getting up and playing on, with the tackle being the only action allowed. A breakdown commences when at least one player from the attacking team is on their feet and over the ball, which is on the ground. Only players acting as a halfback can play the ball with their hands, and they must be on their feet and onside. The tackle assist must release once the tackle occurs. The offside line at the breakdown is the back foot, and all arriving players must come from an onside position and can enter their side of the breakdown midpoint. The video continues with a demonstration of the correct and incorrect postures for riding. The instructor, standing in front of the horse, explains the importance of the position of the seat bones and how it affects the rider's posture. She asks the rider to hollow their back and then come to a neutral position, which will make the seat bones point straight down. The instructor emphasizes that when the rider rounds their back, the seat bones will point differently, leading to an incorrect posture. She uses the analogy of "flashlights on your seat bones" to help the rider visualize the correct position. The instructor also mentions that many riders are taught to take their thighs off the saddle and have their lower leg on, which can result in poor posture. The video shows three lines representing different levels of losing the correct posture, with line three being the most extreme. The instructor stresses the importance of keeping the muscles snugged around the back to maintain the correct posture.
